2026-05-16 15:54:59 | DEBUG | strands_evaluation.instrumentation.agent_plugins | Model response #10 [role=assistant block=1 tool_use] execute_ideal({"intent": "Compute Spearman correlation between ancient Roman city rank and modern city population for cities >1M; match within 0.1 degree; if Barrington Atlas Rank contains 'or', average the two numbers; if multiple ancient cities match a modern city, take the last sample in data; rank modern populations to compute correlation; output correlation rounded to 6 decimals.", "code": "import pandas as pd, numpy as np\nimport re\n\nroman = pd.read_csv('s3://sana-kramabench/datagov/kramabench-archeology-easy-8/files/roman_cities.csv')\nworld = pd.read_csv('s3://sana-kramabench/datagov/kramabench-archeology-easy-11/files/worldcities.csv')\n\n# parse rank to numeric with or\n\ndef parse_rank(x):\n    if pd.isna(x):\n        return np.nan\n    s=str(x).strip()\n    # remove whitespace\n    if 'or' in s:\n        nums=re.findall(r'[-+]?\\d*\\.?\\d+', s)\n        if len(nums)>=2:\n            a=float(nums[0]); b=float(nums[1])\n            return (a+b)/2.0\n    # single number\n    m=re.search(r'[-+]?\\d*\\.?\\d+', s)\n    return float(m.group(0)) if m else np.nan\n\nroman['rank_num']=roman['Barrington Atlas Rank'].apply(parse_rank)\nroman=roman.dropna(subset=['rank_num','Latitude (Y)','Longitude (X)']).copy()\nworld=world.rename(columns={'lat':'lat','lng':'lng'})\nworld['population_num']=pd.to_numeric(world['population'], errors='coerce')\nworld=world.dropna(subset=['population_num','lat','lng']).copy()\nworld=world[world['population_num']>1_000_000].copy()\n\n# For speed, compute distance squared in degrees\nroman_coords=roman[['Latitude (Y)','Longitude (X)']].to_numpy()\nworld_coords=world[['lat','lng']].to_numpy()\n\n# match within 0.1 degrees using euclidean in lat/lng degrees\n# For each world city, find roman indices where within threshold; take last sample (max index in roman dataframe order)\nth=0.1\nth2=th*th\n\nmatch_rank=[]\nmatch_pop=[]\nmatch_pairs=[]\n\nfor i,(wlat,wlng) in enumerate(world_coords):\n    dlat=roman_coords[:,0]-wlat\n    dlng=roman_coords[:,1]-wlng\n    mask=(dlat*dlat + dlng*dlng) <= th2\n    idx=np.where(mask)[0]\n    if idx.size==0:\n        continue\n    j=idx.max()  # last sample in roman data\n    match_rank.append(roman.iloc[j]['rank_num'])\n    match_pop.append(world.iloc[i]['population_num'])\n\n# compute ranks for modern populations (largest population rank=1?) Spearman uses ordinal ranks; for monotonic correlation sign doesn't matter if both ranks reversed? We need rank of modern cities by population presumably (1 highest). Use descending order.\nmodern_ranks=pd.Series(match_pop).rank(method='average', ascending=False)\nroman_ranks=pd.Series(match_rank).rank(method='average', ascending=True)  # rank number: lower barrington rank is better? Use rank_num directly not ordinal of match_rank? Spec: rank of ancient Roman cities -> use Barrington Atlas Rank numeric as rank. If there are gaps doesn't matter. use as is.\nroman_rank_values=np.array(match_rank, dtype=float)\n\n# spearman correlation between roman_rank_values and modern_ranks\n# handle ties in roman_rank_values similarly by ranking it too\nroman_ranks_calc=pd.Series(roman_rank_values).rank(method='average', ascending=True)\n\ncorr=modern_ranks.corr(roman_ranks_calc, method='spearman')\n\ncorr_rounded=round(float(corr),6)\nprint('n_pairs', len(match_rank), 'corr', corr_rounded)\n\ncorr_rounded"}) [toolUseId=call_Lo1WgYjiLblCwK1sf3bDG5YF]
